methods.end:
End of the current range (exclusive).
 
 Calling end() without calling next() at least once results in undefined behavior.

:return: (int) the end of the current range (exclusive).
methods.hasNext:
Checks if the iterator has more ranges. If hasNext() returns false, calling next thereafter results in undefined
 behavior.

:return: (boolean) whether there is another range.
methods.next:
**Incompatible overloads text - text from the first overload:**

Advance the iterator to the next range. Only call after hasNext() has returned true.

*Overload 1*  
  
  
*Overload 2*  
  :param buffer: (short[]) - a short array where consecutive pairs of (start, end-1) values will be stored.
  :param offset: (int) - where in buffer to start storing range boundary values.
  :param maxShortCount: (int) - maximum number of ranges that can be written to buffer; buffer should have at least
          space for 2*maxRanges shorts starting at offset.
  :return: (int) how many ranges were written in buffer; this is two times the individual elements written.
methods.start:
Start of the current range.
 
 Calling start() without calling next() at least once results in undefined behavior.

:return: (int) the start of the current range.
